{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:23:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:23:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16509"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16509"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65873"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51318"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7659"},{"type":"tags","id":"10319"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21823"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65873"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary sensory neurons can be classified based on their structural and functional characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following primary sensory neuron types consists of thinly myelinated fibers with free nerve endings that transmit fast pain signals?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type Ia sensory fibers","Type Ib sensory fibers","Type II sensory fibers","Type III (A-delta) sensory fibers","Type IV (C) sensory fibers"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType III sensory fibers\u003C/strong\u003E (A-delta fibers) are thinly myelinated neurons with free nerve endings that conduct signals at 5-30 m/s and have axon diameters of 1-5 \u03bcm. These fibers are responsible for transmitting fast, sharp pain sensations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other fiber types have different characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia sensory fibers\u003C/strong\u003E (primary muscle spindle afferents) are heavily myelinated and do not have free nerve endings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib sensory fibers\u003C/strong\u003E (Golgi tendon organ afferents) are also heavily myelinated without free nerve endings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II sensory fibers\u003C/strong\u003E (secondary muscle spindle afferents) are moderately myelinated without free nerve endings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType IV sensory fibers\u003C/strong\u003E (C fibers) are unmyelinated, have smaller diameters than A-delta fibers, and conduct more slowly\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA-delta fibers represent an intermediate category between the larger, faster-conducting A-alpha/beta fibers and the smaller, slower-conducting C fibers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A-delta (Type III) nerve fibers are thinly myelinated primary sensory neurons that transmit fast, sharp pain signals.","A-delta fibers have free nerve endings, conduct at 5-30 m/s, and have axon diameters of 1-5 \u03bcm.","A-delta fibers are larger than unmyelinated C fibers but smaller than heavily myelinated A-alpha and A-beta fibers."],"references":["Kiernan MC, Kaji R. Physiology and pathophysiology of myelinated nerve fibers. Handb Clin Neurol. 2013;115:43-53. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-444-52902-2.00004-7. PMID: 23931774.","Hogan QH. Labat lecture: the primary sensory neuron: where it is, what it does, and why it matters. Reg Anesth Pain Med. 2010 May-Jun;35(3):306-11. doi: 10.1097/AAP.0b013e3181d2375e. PMID: 20460965; PMCID: PMC2885292.","Abraira VE, Ginty DD. The sensory neurons of touch. Neuron. 2013 Aug 21;79(4):618-39. doi: 10.1016/j.neuron.2013.07.051. PMID: 23972592; PMCID: PMC3811145.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51318"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16509"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51318"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T12:03:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T12:04:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9200"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65873"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag